{
  "texts": [
    "AWE now broadly encompasses tools that provide both quantitative scores and qualitative feedback within classroom-based formative assessments (Hockly, 2019; Huawei & Aryadoust, 2023), although some AWE tools solely provide qualitative feedback (Burstein et al., 2018).",
    "Automated scores and feedback are generated using algorithms that rely on NLP and AI-primarily supervised machine learning but increasingly LLMs-to deliver automated feedback aimed at enhancing student writing (Correnti et al., 2024; Cotos, 2023; Deeva et al., 2021; Fu et al., 2024; Shi et al., 2022).",
    "AWE is intended to allow educators and learners to customize feedback, aligning it with individual writing goals and pedagogical objectives.",
    "AWE has demonstrated notable benefits in improving writing quality across various contexts, with studies reporting effect sizes ranging from 0.38 to 0.98 in tertiary and second language (L2) settings (Fleckenstein et al., 2023; R. Li, 2023; Ngo et al., 2024; Nunes et al., 2022).",
    "Despite these positive outcomes, the effectiveness of AWE varies significantly by educational level, duration of intervention, and the nature of feedback provided."
  ]
}